You discover a transmembrane protein ALPHA that, like most transmembrane proteins, exhibits a transmembrane domain composed of alpha helices. You next discover that ALPHA serves as a channel. What is a likely amino acid sequence for some portion of the transmembrane domain?  (See <image 1> for one-letter abbreviations)

A. ALILALMWWLLF
B. LMQKPMDSLPDY
C. FPPALGGLPFAMG
D. LKMELAKMILLA
E. ALQQMMDSILDY

To determine the likely amino acid sequence for a portion of the transmembrane domain of a protein, we need to consider the properties of amino acids that typically form alpha helices in transmembrane regions. These amino acids are usually hydrophobic, meaning they do not interact well with water and tend to be found in the interior of proteins or in membrane environments.
